f ‘Onah -- t12 Halakhic and Ethical Background (2): The Dos and Don’ts of Conjugal Relations -- t13 Hasidic Background: Sources and Trends from Early Hasidism -- t14 Kedushah in its Theological Context (1): The Beys Yisroel of Gur -- t15 Kedushah in its Theological Context (2): The Nesives Sholem of Slonim -- t16 Kedushah in its Theological Context (3): The Rebbe of Toldes Aaron -- t17 The Kedushah Polemic -- t18 Kedushah in its Historical Context: Why the 20th Century? -- t19 Kedushah and Modern Hasidic Identity: Intermediate Summary and Conclusion -- tConclusion: Ethos, Custom-in-the-making, Custom, Halakhah-in-the-making, Halakhah: Normative Categories of Jewish Religiosity -- tAppendices -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHasidic groups have myriad customs. While ordinary Jewish law (halakhah) denotes the “bar of holiness” mandated for the ordinary Jew, these customs represent the higher threshold expected of Hasidim, intended to justify their title as hasidim (“pious”). How did the hasidic masters perceive the enactment of these new norms at a time in which the halakhah had already been solidified? How did they explain the normative power of these customs over communities and individuals, and how did they justify customs that diverged from the positive halakhah? This book analyzes the answers given by nineteenth-century hasidic authors. It then examines a test case: kedushah (“holiness”), or sexual abstinence among married men, a particularly restrictive norm enacted by several twentieth-century hasidic groups. Through the use of theoretical tools and historical contextualization, the book elucidates the normative circles of hasidic life, their religious and social sources and their interrelations.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title p